^B@2^*BMovie Maker' Warning: ^*N|cp||at|The following is a short comment by Howard after reviewing this section:

"I don't see anything wrong with the section per se, but I know of no one who plays it like that or who even knows about all those conventional bids.

Most people, at least that I know, who play Gambling 3N, play it as a solid 8 card suit, with no outside aces or kings. I, as you know, use a slightly less well defined method. I play it shows an 8 (or occasionally 9) trick hand with a solid minor. The minor can either be 7 or 8 cards long, but if it is 7 cards long, then you should have an outside A for your 8th trick.

As you also noted, I don't think it is a particularly useful convention, and if someone came up with a better use for opening 3N, I would play it a minute!"

